{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17602971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17602971"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:30:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:30:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15704"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15704"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.08,0.04,0.79,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8395"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62279"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8395"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15704"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47726"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1637"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8503"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20228"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20229"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62279"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA pathologist examines a tissue sample from a 28-year-old woman with chronic pelvic pain. The specimen was obtained from a lesion on the ovarian surface during laparoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following tissue components would confirm a diagnosis of endometriosis in this specimen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Smooth muscle cells","Endometrial stroma only","Endometrial glands only","Endometrial glands and stroma","Inflammatory cells"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of endometriosis requires the presence of both \u003Cstrong\u003Eendometrial glands and stroma\u003C/strong\u003E outside the uterine cavity. Finding only \u003Cstrong\u003Eendometrial glands\u003C/strong\u003E or only \u003Cstrong\u003Eendometrial stroma\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient for diagnosis. While \u003Cstrong\u003Esmooth muscle cells\u003C/strong\u003E may be present in some endometriotic lesions, they are not diagnostic. \u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory cells\u003C/strong\u003E are commonly found around endometriotic implants but are not specific for diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of both glandular and stromal components is essential because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EThese tissues respond to hormonal stimulation similar to normal endometrium\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EThe combination confirms the endometrial origin of the tissue\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EIt helps differentiate endometriosis from other conditions that may involve only one tissue type\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Endometriosis is defined by the presence of endometrial glands and stroma outside the uterine cavity.","Endometriotic lesions contain both endometrial glands and surrounding stromal tissue that respond to hormonal stimulation.","Microscopic diagnosis of endometriosis requires identification of both glandular and stromal elements."],"references":["\u0022Micrograph showing endometriosis (right) and ovarian stroma (left)\u0022 by Nephron is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license.  https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Endometriosis_of_the_ovary.jpg","Burney RO, Giudice LC. Pathogenesis and pathophysiology of endometriosis. Fertil Steril. 2012 Sep;98(3):511-9. doi: 10.1016/j.fertnstert.2012.06.029. Epub 2012 Jul 20. PMID: 22819144; PMCID: PMC3836682","Parasar P, Ozcan P, Terry KL. Endometriosis: Epidemiology, Diagnosis and Clinical Management. Curr Obstet Gynecol Rep. 2017 Mar;6(1):34-41. doi: 10.1007/s13669-017-0187-1. Epub 2017 Jan 27. PMID: 29276652; PMCID: PMC5737931","Smolarz B, Szy\u0142\u0142o K, Romanowicz H. Endometriosis: Epidemiology, Classification, Pathogenesis, Treatment and Genetics (Review of Literature). Int J Mol Sci. 2021 Sep 29;22(19):10554. doi: 10.3390/ijms221910554. PMID: 34638893; PMCID: PMC8508982","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47726"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15704"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21176"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21176","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21176"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dZSe5K9h1p8EQwaq2oDYAy5evbEbB4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dZSe5K9h1p8EQwaq2oDYAy5evbEbB4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1000}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47726"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T15:55:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T15:56:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8395"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62279"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id"